**Explanation:**  
A `debounce` function limits the rate at which a function can execute, ensuring it is not called more frequently than a specified delay, useful for optimizing performance in event-driven scenarios like resizing or scrolling.

```javascript
/**
 * Debounce function to limit the rate at which a function can execute.
 * 
 * @param {Function} func The function to debounce.
 * @param {number} delay The delay in milliseconds.
 * @returns {Function} A debounced version of the function.
 */
function debounce(func, delay) {
    let timeoutId;
    return function (...args) {
        clearTimeout(timeoutId);
        timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
    };
}

// Example usage:
window.addEventListener('resize', debounce(function() {
    console.log('Window resized!');
}, 300));
```

In this example, the `resize` event handler will only log `'Window resized!'` to the console at most once every 300 milliseconds, no matter how frequently the window is actually resized.
